es of Nation Building in Grundtvig and Emerson -- tCommunity and Individuality: Grundtvigian and Kierkegaardian Protestantism in Denmark -- tTransmission -- tGrundtvig’s Idea of a People’s High School and Its Historical Influence -- tGrundtvigianism as Practice and Experience -- tThe Popular Voicing of Sport: Comparative Aspects of Grundtvigian Movement Culture -- tWindmills, Butter, and Bacon: The Circulation of Scientific Knowledge among Grundtvigians in the Decades around 1900 -- tAn Ongoing Influence: The Political Application of Grundtvig’s Ideas in the Debate on Danish Society, 2001–09 -- tThe Economic Consequences of the Size of Nations: Denmark in Comparative Perspective -- tConclusion -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDenmark became a nation amidst the turbulence of the nineteenth century, an era plagued by war, bankruptcy, and territorial loss. Building the Nation is an insightful study of this formation, emphasizing the crucial role of N.F.S. Grundtvig, the father of modern Denmark. Persevering through years of humiliation, internal conflict, and occupation, Denmark now boasts one of the world's most stable and democratic political systems, as well as one of its richest economies. From disaster to success, Building the Nation emphasizes the role of national icons and social movements in the formation of Denmark. The poet, political philosopher, clergyman, and founding father N.F.S. Grundtvig is compared to Rousseau and Durkheim in France, to Herder and Fichte in Germany, and to other great thinkers in the United States and Ireland. During his lifetime, the kingdom of Denmark transformed from monarchy to democracy and moved from agrarianism to a modern economy - evolutions to which Grundtvig himself contributed. He has become a fundamental and inescapable reference-point for discussions about nation, democracy, freedom, religion, and education in Denmark and abroad. Situating Grundtvig in both the history of Denmark and the intellectual history of nineteenth-century Europe, Building the Nation argues for the centrality of his influence in the making of modern Denmark, as well as the continuing influence of his work.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAuthors, Danishy19th centuryvBiography. 0aElectronic books. 0aLutheran ChurchzDenmarkxClergyvBiography. 0aPhilosopherszDenmarkvBiography. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Scandinavia.2bisacsh1 aBaunvig, Katrine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBuckser, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBugge, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBöss, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCampbell, John L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDalsgaard, Matias Møl, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDamsholt, Tine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEichberg, Henning, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFukuyama, Francis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHall, John A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHjermitslev, Hans Henrik, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJensen, Jason O., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJonas, Uffe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKorsgaard, Ove, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aKorsgaard, Ove, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLarsen, Esben Lunde, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/voca